# Iteration 4 - keep - score: 0.9224
Operation: REWORD
Reasoning: The dominant failures are hallucination and boundary confusion, especially in tasks and decisions: the model is extracting aspirations, descriptive statements, and conditional plans as concrete state items. Existing rules mention concrete state, but they do not clearly distinguish implementation choices from explicit decisions or exclude milestone goals and contingent follow-ons from tasks. I chose REWORD on the extractability rule because it already covers these categories, making a sharper boundary higher-impact than adding another overlapping rule; I rejected ADD because prior additions on similar themes risk redundancy and dilution.

- - Treat items as extractable only when they are stated as concrete project state: tasks are assigned, planned, in-progress, blocked, or completed work items; decisions are explicit agreements or adopted choices; people are named individuals with roles; project owner is the person stated as owning the project or product side. Do not extract background descriptions, role statements, aspirations, or possible future ideas as tasks or decisions.
+ - Treat items as extractable only when they are stated as concrete project state: tasks are assigned, planned, in-progress, blocked, or completed work items; decisions are explicit agreements or adopted choices that set approach, scope, policy, or tooling; people are named individuals with their stated role or responsibility wording; project owner is the person stated as owning the project or product side. Do not extract project names, background descriptions, role statements as tasks, implementation details that merely explain how something works, milestone goals or desired outcomes, conditional next steps, or possible future ideas as tasks or decisions.
